```def calculate_requests(S, alpha, kappa):
    """Calculate the number of requests allowed based on stakes."""
    R = alpha * (S / (1 + kappa * S))
    return R

# Function to print requests for different kappas
def experiment_with_kappa(S1, S2, alpha, kappas):
    for kappa in kappas:
        R1 = calculate_requests(S1, alpha, kappa)
        R2 = calculate_requests(S2, alpha, kappa)
        ratio = R2 / R1
        print(f"kappa: {kappa:.10f} - Requests for {S1} stakes: {R1:.2f}, Requests for {S2} stakes: {R2:.2f}, Ratio: {ratio:.2f}")

# Stake values
S1 = 10000
S2 = 1000000
alpha = 1

# Different kappa values to experiment with
# as kappa grows, request becomes more equitable.
kappas = [1e-8, 1e-7, 3.38e-7, 5e-7, 1e-6, 1e-5]

The decision to switch aligns closely with the vision and objectives of the subnet. The number of AI models on Bittensor has experienced exponential growth. Omron's purpose is to bridge consumers of verified inference from external networks to Bittensor. To ensure that predictions are generated from decentralized or off-chain sources without tampering or misrouting, we utilize zero-knowledge cryptography. This approach offers the advantage of cryptographic proofs and verification that do not rely on a centralized authority. Even if Omron were to cease operations, the work remains open-source, on-chain, and immutable.

Given the rapid advancements and diversity in the AI tech stack, proving systems must be incentivized to evolve continuously. Not all proving systems will be optimized for every model, and this is where Omron plays a crucial role. We aim to ensure that miners and developers are motivated to distill larger models into succinctly verifiable models, optimize the entire MLOps stack, and discover innovative ways to enhance proving systems.

Although we initially launched with EZKL, we are exhaustively exploring other proving systems (both open-source and proprietary) to achieve computational parity with the original inference request. Omron will remain proving system-agnostic, fostering improvements through competitive dynamics. 

We have also noticed fragmentation in benchmarking these systems.  As part of our strategy, we aim to establish Omron as a single source of truth and standards for benchmarking proving systems in a live on-chain environment. In line with Bittensor's commitment to open participation, we will publish all on-chain optimizations and results on https://brainbench.xyz/.

Hi @Onyx,

The Circom proof system has been used prevalently in broader Web3 for quite some time now, and has been used in projects such as Polygon Hermez and Iden3, making it a reliable and battle tested zero knowledge framework.

In terms of it’s implementation in Omron, we were able to achieve high degrees of optimization through the manual implementation of proof of weights circuits in the Circom proof system (approximately 50% faster proving times and 95% smaller proofs compared to EZKL implementations) while preserving output accuracy. This allows the network to perform to a higher degree for these kinds of circuits and served as impetus for this change.

As Ron mentioned above, we are proof system agnostic. While Circom is a better fit for proof of weights, we are constantly evaluating both new and existing proof systems for integration into Omron. There are two major implementations in progress which continue this aspect of the roadmap, including implementations of proof of weights in the Jolt proof system https://github.com/a16z/jolt and re-introduction of a larger Benqi LSTM model, which will run predictions based on realtime external blockchain data to provide forecasted TVL prediction for the Benqi protocol (https://benqi.fi/).

We have recently published a medium article further detailing this update here:
